# Markdown Formatting for Pandoc PDF Compilation

When editing any markdown (`*.md`) files, follow these formatting rules to ensure proper PDF compilation with pandoc.

## YAML Front Matter Header

Every document intended for pandoc PDF compilation **must** include a complete YAML front matter block at the top of the file. Use the following template as the standard header:

```markdown
---
title: "Document Title"
subtitle: "Document Subtitle"
author:
  - "Author Name^[Affiliation]"
  - "Second Author^[Other Affiliation]"
date: "Month YYYY"
numbersections: true
lang: en
documentclass: article
geometry: "left=2.5cm,right=2.5cm,top=2.5cm,bottom=2.5cm"
toc: true
header-includes:
  - \usepackage{fancyhdr}
  - \pagestyle{fancy}
  - \fancyhf{}
  - \fancyhead[L]{\nouppercase{\leftmark}}
  - \fancyhead[R]{\thepage}
  - \renewcommand{\headrulewidth}{0.4pt}
---
```

### Field Reference

| Field | Required | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `title` | Yes | Main document title |
| `subtitle` | Recommended | Secondary title line |
| `author` | Recommended | List of authors; use `^[Affiliation]` footnote syntax for affiliations |
| `date` | Recommended | Written-out month and year, e.g. `"March 2026"` |
| `numbersections` | Yes | Set `true` to enable automatic section numbering |
| `lang` | Yes | BCP 47 language tag, e.g. `en` or `de` |
| `documentclass` | Yes | Use `article` for standard documents |
| `geometry` | Recommended | Page margins; `2.5cm` all sides is a sensible default |
| `toc` | Recommended | Set `true` to generate a table of contents |
| `header-includes` | Recommended | LaTeX preamble snippets; the fancyhdr block shown above produces section name on left and page number on right |

### Notes

- Use `lang: de` for German-language documents.
- The `^[Affiliation]` syntax in author names produces a footnote on the title page.
- Do **not** put a `# Title` heading in the document body; the title comes from the YAML `title` field.

## List Formatting

**Lists must be separated from surrounding text with blank lines:**

- Add a blank line **before** the first list item
- Add a blank line **after** the last list item
- Do **not** add blank lines **between** list items (unless starting a new list)

### Example - Correct

```markdown
This is a paragraph before the list.

- First item
- Second item
- Third item

This is a paragraph after the list.
```

### Example - Incorrect

```markdown
This is a paragraph before the list.
- First item

- Second item

- Third item
This is a paragraph after the list.
```

## Section Numbering

**Never manually number sections when using automatic numbering:**

- When the YAML header contains `numbersections: true`, pandoc will automatically number all sections
- Do **not** include manual numbering in section headings (e.g., "1.", "2.1", etc.)
- Manual numbering will result in double numbering in the PDF output

### Example - Correct

```markdown
---
numbersections: true
---

# Introduction

## Background

## Methodology

# Results
```

### Example - Incorrect

```markdown
---
numbersections: true
---

# 1. Introduction

## 1.1 Background

## 1.2 Methodology

# 2. Results
```

## Section Nesting

**Always use proper heading hierarchy:**

- Use YAML header for document `title` and `subtitle` (not markdown headings)
- Start document sections at level 1 (`#`)
- Nest subsections in proper order: level 1 → level 2 → level 3
- **Never skip heading levels** (e.g., level 1 → level 3)
- **Never start with level 2** when level 1 hasn't been used yet

### Example - Correct

```markdown
---
title: "My Document"
subtitle: "A Great Subtitle"
---

# First Major Section

This is content.

## First Subsection

More content.

### Detail Level

Even more detail.

## Second Subsection

Content here.

# Second Major Section

New major topic.
```

### Example - Incorrect

```markdown
---
title: "My Document"
subtitle: "A Great Subtitle"
---

## First Section (WRONG - should be #)

### Subsection (WRONG - skipped level 2)

# Another Section

#### Too deep (WRONG - skipped levels 2 and 3)
```

## Code Blocks and Lists

**Code blocks within or after lists need proper spacing:**

- Add blank line before code block
- Code blocks break list continuation unless properly indented

### Example - Correct

```markdown
Here is an introduction:

- Item with code example:

```json
{
  "key": "value"
}
```

- Next item
```

## Symbols and Unicode Characters

**Avoid Unicode characters that are not supported by the default LaTeX fonts.**

When compiling with `--pdf-engine=xelatex` and the default Latin Modern fonts, many Unicode symbols (subscripts, superscripts, special mathematical characters) are missing from the font and produce `[WARNING] Missing character` errors in the PDF output.

### Subscripts and Superscripts

Never use Unicode subscript/superscript characters. Use LaTeX inline math mode instead:

| Avoid (Unicode) | Use instead (LaTeX math) | Renders as |
|-----------------|--------------------------|------------|
| `CO₂` (U+2082) | `CO$_2$` | CO₂ |
| `H₂O` | `H$_2$O` | H₂O |
| `m²` (U+00B2) | `m$^2$` | m² |
| `kgCO₂e` | `kgCO$_2$e` | kgCO₂e |

Inline math syntax: `$...$` — single `$` on each side, no spaces between `$` and the content.

### Safe Unicode Characters

These Unicode characters are generally safe with xelatex + Latin Modern fonts:

- Standard German umlauts: ä, ö, ü, Ä, Ö, Ü, ß
- Common punctuation: „ " ' ' – — (German quotation marks, en/em dash)
- Section symbol: § (U+00A7)
- Degree symbol: ° (U+00B0)
- Euro sign: € (U+20AC) — requires `\usepackage{eurosym}` in a custom template, or use `EUR` as text fallback

### Symbols Requiring LaTeX Packages

For other special symbols, prefer LaTeX commands over Unicode:

- Omega/Ohm: `$\Omega$` instead of Ω
- Arrows in text: `$\rightarrow$` instead of →, or use pandoc's `→` which renders fine in most engines

## Tables

### Required Packages

Pandoc renders markdown tables as `longtable` + `booktabs`. Include these in `header-includes` for reliable output:

```yaml
header-includes:
  - \usepackage{longtable}
  - \usepackage{booktabs}
  - \usepackage{array}
  - \usepackage{ragged2e}
  - |
    ```{=latex}
    \setlength\LTleft{0pt}
    \setlength\LTright{0pt}
    \usepackage{etoolbox}
    \AtBeginEnvironment{longtable}{\small\RaggedRight}
    \setlength{\LTpre}{0pt}
    \setlength{\LTpost}{0pt}
    ```
```

- `longtable` — tables that span multiple pages
- `booktabs` — professional horizontal rules
- `ragged2e` — `\RaggedRight` for better hyphenation than `\raggedright`
- `\LTleft/\LTright` at `0pt` — stretch tables to full text width
- `\small\RaggedRight` on every longtable — smaller font + ragged-right wrapping prevents overflow
- `\LTpre/\LTpost` at `0pt` — removes extra vertical space above/below tables

### Controlling Column Widths

Pandoc derives relative column widths from the **number of dashes** in the separator row. More dashes = proportionally wider column.

```markdown
| Attribute | LMT | Comments |
|------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----|---------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `expectedLifetimeChargeDischargeCycles` | M | Descriptive text that wraps nicely |
```

Rules of thumb:

- Give **narrow columns** (flags, codes, short labels) 4–10 dashes
- Give **content columns** (names, descriptions) dashes proportional to expected content length
- The **comments/description column** should dominate (≥ 40% of total dashes) when it has the longest prose
- The **total** number of dashes across all columns scales the overall table width — keep it consistent within a document

Example ratios for a 7-column attribute table (A4 portrait, ~16 cm text width):

| Column | Dashes | Approx. % |
|--------|--------|-----------|
| Attribute name | 78 | 42 % |
| LMT flag | 4 | 2 % |
| Level | 6 | 3 % |
| Data source | 10 | 5 % |
| Static/Dynamic | 10 | 5 % |
| Comments | 69 | 37 % |
| Verification | 6 | 3 % |

### Landscape Tables

For very wide tables, switch a single page to landscape with `pdflscape`:

```yaml
header-includes:
  - \usepackage{pdflscape}
```

```markdown
```{=latex}
\begin{landscape}
```

| Very wide table | ... |
|-----------------|-----|

```{=latex}
\end{landscape}
```
```

## Cross-References

Pandoc includes `hyperref` automatically for PDF output — `\autoref` is always available without an extra `\usepackage`.

### Section Labels

Assign a label to a heading with pandoc's `{#id}` syntax:

```markdown
# My Chapter {#sec:mychapter}

## My Subsection {#sec:mysub}
```

This is the **only** correct way to label sections. A raw `\label{sec:x}` placed after a heading is **not** attached to the heading counter and will produce `??` when referenced.

### Use `\autoref`, not `\ref`

**Always use `\autoref{sec:id}` for section cross-references.** Do not write a manual "Kapitel"/"Section" prefix and do not use `~\ref{}`.

**Why not `~\ref{}`?** Pandoc escapes a lone `~` in markdown text to `\textasciitilde{}` in the LaTeX output, which renders as a visible tilde character `~` rather than a non-breaking space. `\autoref` handles the prefix word and spacing automatically.

| Avoid | Use instead | PDF output |
|-------|-------------|------------|
| `Kapitel~\ref{sec:roadmap}` | `\autoref{sec:roadmap}` | Kapitel 9 |
| `Abschnitt~\ref{sec:backup}` | `\autoref{sec:backup}` | Abschnitt 5.4 |
| `Section~\ref{sec:intro}` | `\autoref{sec:intro}` | Section 2 |

### Configure `\autoref` Names

The default English names (`Section`, `Subsection`) need overriding for German documents. Add to the `{=latex}` preamble block in `header-includes`:

```yaml
header-includes:
  - |
    ```{=latex}
    \def\sectionautorefname{Kapitel}
    \def\subsectionautorefname{Abschnitt}
    \def\subsubsectionautorefname{Abschnitt}
    ```
```

### Figure and Table Labels

Place `\label{fig:id}` **inside** the caption alt-text so LaTeX attaches it to the figure counter:

```markdown
![Caption text \label{fig:overview}](image.png){width=\linewidth}

See Figure \ref{fig:overview} for details.
```

Use `\ref{fig:x}` (not `\autoref`) for figures/tables — you write the type word ("Figure", "Abbildung") explicitly. If `\label` is placed outside the alt-text it captures the surrounding section counter instead.

### Troubleshooting `??` References

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
|---------|-------|-----|
| Section ref is `??` | Heading missing `{#sec:id}` | Add `{#sec:id}` to the heading |
| Figure ref is `??` | `\label{}` outside caption alt-text | Move `\label{}` inside the alt-text |
| `??` despite correct label | Compiled only once | Compile twice; LaTeX resolves refs on second pass |
| Figure environments broken | `--from=markdown-implicit_figures` flag used | Remove that flag; keep `implicit_figures` enabled |

## Quick Reference

| Element | Rule | Example |
|---------|------|---------|
| Lists | Blank lines before and after, not between items | `text` then blank line then `- item` |
| Sections | No manual numbering with `numbersections: true` | `# Introduction` not `# 1. Introduction` |
| Nesting | Start at level 1, never skip levels | `#` → `##` → `###` |
| Title | Use YAML header, not markdown heading | `title: "Doc Title"` |
| Subscripts | LaTeX inline math, not Unicode | `CO$_2$` not `CO₂` |
| Superscripts | LaTeX inline math, not Unicode | `m$^2$` not `m²` |
| Table width | More dashes in separator = wider column | `\|---\|--------\|` → narrow, wide |
| Table overflow | Use `\small\RaggedRight` via `\AtBeginEnvironment` | see Tables section |
| Section label | Pandoc `{#id}` on the heading line | `# My Chapter {#sec:mychapter}` |
| Section ref | `\autoref{sec:id}` — no manual prefix or tilde | `\autoref{sec:mychapter}` |
| Figure label | `\label{fig:id}` inside caption alt-text | `![Caption \label{fig:x}](img.png)` |
| Figure ref | `\ref{fig:id}` with explicit type word | `Figure \ref{fig:x}` |

## Validation

Before committing markdown files intended for pandoc PDF compilation:

1. Confirm a complete YAML front matter block is present with at least `title`, `numbersections`, `lang`, `documentclass`, and `geometry`
2. Check all lists have blank lines before/after
3. Verify no manual section numbering exists
4. Confirm proper heading hierarchy (no skipped levels)
5. Ensure title/subtitle are in YAML header, not as markdown headings
6. Replace Unicode subscripts/superscripts with LaTeX math (`$_x$` / `$^x$`)
7. Tables: `longtable`, `booktabs`, `array`, `ragged2e` in `header-includes`; `\LTleft/\LTright` at `0pt`; `\small\RaggedRight` applied globally
8. Table column widths tuned via separator dash lengths — description columns get the most dashes
9. Every cross-referenced section heading has a `{#sec:id}` label
10. Section refs use `\autoref{sec:id}`, not `Word~\ref{sec:id}`
